<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26071a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26071a">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26071a"> 71(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> woad</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">All the Britons stained themselves of a blue colour with <mark>woad</mark>, which gave them a more horrible appearance in battle. <small> Sharon Turner, <a name="HOAG" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HOAG"><cite title="source">The History of The Anglo-Saxons</cite></a> (1820) 76</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Woad: a yellow-flowered European plant of the cabbage family. It was formerly widely grown in Britain as a source of blue dye, which was extracted from the leaves after they had been dried, powdered, and fermented. </mm> </dd></dl>
